04842nam a22007215i 9780226706948DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019044527  a97802267069487 a10.7208/97802267069482doi  a(DE-B1597)566575  a(OCoLC)1157089372  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aRS67.G8bD675 2020 4aRS67.G8bD675 2021 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a338.47615109412231 aDorner, Zachary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMerchants of Medicines :bThe Commerce and Coercion of Health in Britain’s Long Eighteenth Century /cZachary Dorner. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b24 halftones, 5 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tIntroduction -- tOne. Toward an Industry -- tTwo. Distance’s Remedies -- tThree. The Possibility of Unfree Markets -- tFour. Pine Trees and Profits -- tFive. Self-Sufficiency in a Bottle -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe period from the late seventeenth to the early nineteenth century—the so-called long eighteenth century of English history—was a time of profound global change, marked by the expansion of intercontinental empires, long-distance trade, and human enslavement. It was also the moment when medicines, previously produced locally and in small batches, became global products. As greater numbers of British subjects struggled to survive overseas, more medicines than ever were manufactured and exported to help them. Most historical accounts, however, obscure the medicine trade’s dependence on slave labor, plantation agriculture, and colonial warfare. In Merchants of Medicines, Zachary Dorner follows the earliest industrial pharmaceuticals from their manufacture in the United Kingdom, across trade routes, and to the edges of empire, telling a story of what medicines were, what they did, and what they meant. He brings to life business, medical, and government records to evoke a vibrant early modern world of London laboratories, Caribbean estates, South Asian factories, New England timber camps, and ships at sea. In these settings, medicines were produced, distributed, and consumed in new ways to help confront challenges of distance, labor, and authority in colonial territories. Merchants of Medicines offers a new history of economic and medical development across early America, Britain, and South Asia, revealing the unsettlingly close ties among medicine, finance, warfare, and slavery that changed people’s expectations of their health and their bodies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aPharmaceutical industryzGreat BritainxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAmerica.  aAtlantic World.  aBritain.  aCaribbean.  aEarly Modern.  acapitalism.  aempire.  amedicine.  amerchants.  aslavery.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226706948423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226706948.jpg  a978-3-11-069309-6  UChP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  